The political leaders of the UK and the EU each want to sign a trade agreement, but neither knows of the other's attitude. Suppose a neutral party organises a diplomatic meeting. Each leader can choose to 'Declare' an interest in the trade agreement or 'Reject' it. If both the UK and EU 'Declare' they get positive political returns from the trade \textit{agreement}  ($u_{a}$+b and $u_{a}$ for UK and EU, respectively, noting that the UK has more to gain than the EU $b>0$). If one Agrees and the other Rejects this hurts the former's reputation (implying the 'loser' payoff $u_l$). Rejecting an 'Agree' offer from the other side makes the leader look 'strong' yielding $u_s$. If both play Reject, they each get the ('no deal') $u_n$. The payoff matrix is given below, where $u_{a}>u_{s}>u_{m}>u_{l}$ and $b>0$.

