\includegraphics[height=3in]{monopnosupply.ong}

\question[3] Which of the following are true statements – choose all that apply

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item For a firm to be a monopoly it must be that average costs in this industry decline in output over the entire range of potential outputs.
\item A monopoly does not face a 'demand curve' in a meaningful sense, as its demand curve can rotate over time in response to changes in price. 
\item The monopoly maximises its profit by charging the price where marginal revenue equals marginal costs (as long as this price is above average costs)
\item A monopoly does not have a 'supply curve': depending on the slope of and intercept of the demand curve, the monopoly may provide the same quantity at a different price or a different quantity at the same price.
\item the producer surplus of a monopoly is less than that of a firm under perfect competition
\end{enumerate}

\begin{solution}
True statements:

The monopoly maximises its profit by charging the price where marginal revenue equals marginal costs (as long as this price is above average costs) -- in fact this is true of firms under basically any market structure, including monopoly.

AND

A monopoly does not have a 'supply curve': depending on the slope of and intercept of the demand curve, the monopoly may provide the same quantity at a different price or a different quantity at the same price Note that a monopoly does not have a 'supply curve', as its profit-maximising price changes in response to a rotation in the demand curve.

The other statements are false. Diminishing average costs may lead to the situation of a natural monopoly, but this is not a necessary condition for there to be a monopoly; there may also be legal barriers to entry.

A monopoly faces a demand curve just like a firm under any other market structure.

A monopoly will gain a producer surplus, while a firm under perfect competition will not.
\end{solution}
\end{minipage}

