\question[4]  \textcolor{gray}{\textit{Choose ONE.}}
Consider the choice between two binary lotteries $A$ and $B$. Lottery $A$ will pay $A_1$ with probability p and $A_0$ with probability $1-p$, where $A_1>A_0$. Lottery $B$ will pay $B_1$ with probability $q$ and $B_0$ with probability $1-q$, where $B_1>B_0$. Each lottery costs the same amount to obtain. Assume all people prefer more money to less money. Which of the following is true?

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
  \item If each lottery is a coin flip, i.e., $p=q=1/2$, and $A_1=B_1=\pounds10$, a risk-neutral person will definitely choose lottery $B$ if $A_0>B_0$.
  \item If each lottery is a coin flip, i.e., $p=q=1/2$, $A_0 =\pounds 0$, $A_1 =\pounds 10$,  $B_0 =\pounds 4.50$, and $B_1 =\pounds 5.50$ a risk-averse  person will definitely choose lottery $B$.
  \item If $A_0=B_0=\pounds2$, $A_1=B_1=\pounds10$, $p=0.4$ and $q=0.5$ a risk-averse person will definitely choose lottery A.
  \item  If $A_0 =\pounds 0$, $A_1 =\pounds 10$,  $B_0 =\pounds 0.9$, and $B_1 =\pounds 1$ and $p=q=0.1$, a risk-averse  person will definitely choose lottery $B$

\end{enumerate}
\begin{solution}
  If $A_0 =\pounds 0$, $A_1 =\pounds 10$,  $B_0 =\pounds 0.9$, and $B_1 =\pounds 1$ and $p=q=0.1$, a risk-averse  person will definitely choose lottery $B$.

This is because It has the same expected monetary value (\pounds 1) but less variation in payoffs (\pounds 0.9 vs 0 in the bad state and \pounds 1 versus 10 in the good state)

Note, this is perhaps slightly more tricky than I would ask you on an exam. 


\end{solution}

\end{minipage}

