Question text:
\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\question[4] \textcolor{black}{\textit{There are between 1 and 5 correct answers; partial credit will be awarded.}}
The `lemons model' of asymmetric information (Akerlof, 1970), for the case that leads to inefficient outcomes (missing markets),  assumes:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\Alph*)]  \item The value of the used car is uncertain; it follows (e.g.) a uniform distribution, and neither the potential buyer nor seler knows any more than this.
  \item Sellers have a strong `endowment effect', and thus would accept less for the car than they would be willing to pay for it.
  \item The seller values a car of a particular quality more than the potential buyer.
  \item The potential buyer values a car of a particular quality more than the seller.
  \item Sellers and buyers can write complete and enforceable contracts over the ex-post observed  true value of the car.
  \item The seller has a 'hidden action' she can take, which the buyer does not observe directly.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{solution}
The potential buyer values a car of a particular quality more than the seller. This condition is necessary to ensure that 'trade increases surplus, so the absence of trade reduces it.'
\end{solution}
\end{minipage}
